Because $\triangle AIB$ in center is an isosceles triangle, then $\angle ABE=\angle IBE, \angle AIB=180-2\angle IBE$, because $\angle ABE = 90-\frac{\angle ACB}{2}$. Further this leads us to $$\frac{\angle AIE}{2}=180-2\angle IBE=180^{ \circ}-2(\angle AEB-\angle ABE)$$
because $\sin \alpha= \sin(180-\alpha)$ and  $\angle AEB=90^{ \circ}-\frac{\angle ACB}{2}$. Now we get:
\begin{align*}
\frac{\angle AIE}{2}&=180^{ \circ}-2\left(90^{ \circ}-\frac{\angle AEB}{2}-90^{ \circ}+\frac{\angle ACB}{2}\right)\\
\angle AIE&=360^{ \circ}-2\left(180^{ \circ}-34^{ \circ}\right)\\
&=2^{ \circ}
\end{align*}
We are done.</thought> <answer> $2^{ \circ}$ </answer>

